Parental age and offspring mortality: Negative effects of reproductive ageing 
may be counterbalanced by secular increases in longevity.

Barclay K(1)(2)(3), Myrskylä M(1)(3)(4).

Author information:
(1)a Max Planck Institute for Demographic Research.
(2)b Stockholm University.
(3)c London School of Economics and Political Science.
(4)d University of Helsinki.

As parental ages at birth continue to rise, concerns about the effects of 
fertility postponement on offspring are increasing. Due to reproductive ageing, 
advanced parental ages have been associated with negative health outcomes for 
offspring, including decreased longevity. The literature, however, has neglected 
to examine the potential benefits of being born at a later date. Secular 
declines in mortality mean that later birth cohorts are living longer. We 
analyse mortality over ages 30-74 among 1.9 million Swedish men and women born 
1938-60, and use a sibling comparison design that accounts for all 
time-invariant factors shared by the siblings. When incorporating cohort 
improvements in mortality, we find that those born to older mothers do not 
suffer any significant mortality disadvantage, and that those born to older 
fathers have lower mortality. These findings are likely to be explained by 
secular declines in mortality counterbalancing the negative effects of 
reproductive ageing.

