BACKGROUND: Escalating health care spending is a concern in Western countries, 
given the lack of evidence of a direct connection between spending and 
improvements in health. We aimed to determine the association between spending 
on health care and social programs and health outcomes in Canada.
METHODS: We used retrospective data from Canadian provincial expenditure 
reports, for the period 1981 to 2011, to model the effects of social and health 
spending (as a ratio, social/health) on potentially avoidable mortality, infant 
